President Obama released a statement on the six-year anniversary of Hurricane Katrina, emphasizing the importance of continued efforts to help New Orleans and the Gulf Coast fully recover. He acknowledged the resilience and determination of the people in rebuilding their communities and highlighted the federal government's role in providing funding for recovery, supporting school systems, and assisting displaced families. The President also mentioned the administration's efforts to enhance disaster preparedness and strengthen recovery capabilities. He referenced Hurricane Irene as an example of the ongoing partnership between the federal government and local communities in responding to and recovering from disasters. Lastly, President Obama emphasized the long-term needs of communities impacted by disasters and reassured that his administration will continue to support them until the work is done.